794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.0b1d0147-b739-4d52-a12f-03ccd9b52b89.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.
794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.39ddabf2-bb6c-4dba-a0a4-f3f659691901.description=
Insert a new name/value property into a JSON Object, where the value is a String.  

This operation will force the value of the name/vale pair to be a String, no matter what data type it actually is. This means
that the newPropertyValue input does not need to be wrapped in quotes, and any quotes entered in this input will be escaped, 
and end up in the properties' value. 

The operation 'Add JSON Property to Object' should be used to add values of type other than String, for example\: another Object, 
an Array, or a Number. 

Examples\: 
1)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: test_value
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"test_value"}

2)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: "test_value"
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"\"test_value\""}
3)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: 1
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"1"}
4)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: [1,2,3,4]
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"[1,2,3,4]"}
         Note the value in the name/value pair above is not a JSON Array, it is just a plain string that looks like one. 

Inputs\:
    jsonObject - String representation of a JSON Object. Objects in JSON are a collection of name value pairs, sepperated by a colon and 
                         surrounded with curly brackets {}. The name must be a string value, and the value can be a single string or any valid
                         JSON Object or Array.
Examples\: {"one"\:1, "two"\:2}, {"one"\:{"a"\:"a","B"\:"B"}, "two"\:"two", "three"\:[1,2,3.4]}
    newPropertyName - The name of the new property to add to the JSON object. 
Examples\: property1, some_property, another property
    newPropertyValue - The value for the new property. This is interpreted as a string, no matter what the contents of the input. 
Examples\: value1, another value


Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation failed. See the message in returnResult for details


Results\:
    returnResult - The new JSON array with the inserted element.
794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.45f6848a-1912-48ce-93f9-31ef696b27ea.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.
794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.4615c9ee-ebd1-4916-b163-d7b373e07006.description=Replaces a substring within a string. 
Inputs\:
input - the master string.
replace - the text to replace.
replaceWith - the text to replace with.

Results\:
the string with the text replaced.

Responses\:
success - succeeded in updating string.
failure - was unable to replace for some reason
794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.4e64f363-3670-4b92-907b-397b3a057f8c.description=
Service to perform an HTTP POST using the Java HTTP Client. The data to be POST-ed can be supplied as either a raw string value or a file, whose contents are encoded and sent as the body of the POST request.

Inputs\:
    endpoint - The endpoint to use for the request.
    uri - The URI to add to the endpoint in order to makeup the URL for the request 
    authToken - The authentication token used for the request.
Example\: HPAuth_4f3b5044e4b05c3dbefdee82
    file - A file to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method. This should be the path to a file/document on the disk. The  and  inputs are mutually exclusive, the operation failing if both are supplied.
    string - The raw text to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method. The  and  inputs are mutually exclusive, the operation failing if both are supplied.
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication)
Default value\: anonymous (no authentication used when executing the request)
    kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the  (Key Distribution Center) and  get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    contentType - The type of content, set in the request header, representing the message body data MIME-type.
Examples\: "text/html", "text/html; charset\=UTF-8", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded".
    characterSet - The character encoding of the text to be posted. If you do not specify a value for this input, it will be taken from the  field, specified in the  input. If the  field is absent, it will take the default value.
Default value\: ISO-8859-1
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    proxy - The hostname or IP address of the computer that acts as proxy server.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The proxy server user name.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL or not. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL or not. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. 
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file.
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. 
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.
    headerNamesList - A list of header names to be used for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - A list of header values to be used for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - A list of query parameter names to be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - A list of query parameter values to be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separate list elements.
Default value\: (carriage return)

Results\: 
    document - This is the primary output. The result from HTTP Client operations, which is the body of the HTTP document returned by the call. 
    responseHeaders - A list containing all the headers of the response message, separated by the delimiter.
    exception - The stack trace of the thrown error (if an error occurred).
    FailureMessage - The final error message returned to the user.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    unknown - The POST was not fully processed, the server responded with an informational response or The specified URL has moved.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
See the 'Library/Operations/HTTP Client/' operations for additional information.
794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.61d27a96-226b-448c-9641-37e6d8ff7efc.description=
Inserts a new name/value property into a JSON object, where the value is a valid JSON string. If the  input is not a valid string representation of a JSON object, the operation fails.
The 'Add Property to Object' operation can be used to add a property with a simple string value. 

Examples\: 
1)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: [1,2,3]
     Result\:
         { "test"\:[1,2,3]}
2)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: {"a"\:"b"}
     Result\:
         { "test"\:{"a"\:"b"}}
3)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: 1
     Result\:
         { "test"\:1}

Inputs\:
    jsonObject - String representation of a JSON object. Objects in JSON are a collection of name value pairs, separated by a colon and surrounded with curly brackets {}. The name must be a string value, and the value can be a single string or any valid JSON object or array.
Examples\: {"one"\:1, "two"\:2}, {"one"\:{"a"\:"a","B"\:"B"}, "two"\:"two", "three"\:[1,2,3.4]}
    newPropertyName - The name of the new property to add to the JSON object. 
Examples\: property1, some_property, another property
    newPropertyValue - The value for the new property. This must be a valid JSON representation of a JavaScript object.
Examples\: 1, {"A"\:"A"}, [1,2,3,4]

Results\:
    Result - The JSON array with the inserted element.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. See the message in  for details.
794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.78574afc-fae3-4fc0-b973-d2c2c1a1a989.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
string1 - The first string.
string2 - The second string.
ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

responses\:
true - If the two strings are equal
false - If the two strings are not equal

794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.c0bc41a8-e37d-40bc-a38b-63e30e1c3818.description=
Insert a new name/value parameter into a JSON Object. 

This Operation differes from the 'Add to Array' operation in that this one will try and validate the new element as
a JSON object, whereas 'Add to Array' will just wrap the element in quotes and treat it as a string. This means 
that the element passed into this operation must be a valid JSON object, or the operation will fail. 

When specifying the index to an array element in javascript it is possible to use the standard notation, where the 1st 
element from the left is index 0, and the right-most element is (n-1), in an array with n elements. However, 
it is also possible to specify elements starting from the right side of the array using negative numbers, in which case
the right-most element is referred to by index -1 and the left-most element is at position (-1 * n), again for an array with n elements.

Inputs\:
    jsonObject - String representation of a JSON Object. Objects in JSON are a collection of name value pairs, sepperated by a colon and 
                         surrounded with curly brackets {}. The name must be a string value, and the value can be a single string or any valid
                         JSON Object or Array.
Examples\: {"one"\:1, "two"\:2}, {"one"\:{"a"\:"a","B"\:"B"}, "two"\:"two", "three"\:[1,2,3.4]}
    newPropertyName - The name of the new property to add to the JSON object. 
Examples\: property1, some_property, another property
    newPropertyValue - The value for the new property. This is interpreted as a string, no matter what the contents of the input. 
Example\: value1, another value


Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation failed. See the message in returnResult for details


Results\:
    returnResult - The new JSON array with the inserted element.

794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.description=
Creates a new server instance using a given image and a virtual hardware configuration (flavor). You can attach user defined metadata to the new server, using the  input. The metadata format is a JSON object with name/value pairs for the metadata items.
At creation time, up to 5 small files (<1kb) can be injected into the server's file system. You can specify these files using the  input, which is a JSON array of objects. Each JSON object contains a 'path' property, which is the full path to the file on the server you are creating, and a 'contents' property, which is the content of the file to create, base64 encoded. If needed, you can look for an operation under 'Library/Utility Operations/Base64 Encoder' to dynamically encode file contents. 

Inputs\:
    computeEndpoint - The endpoint to which requests are sent. 
    authToken - The authentication token used for the request.
Example\: HPAuth_4f3b5044e4b05c3dbefdee82
    name - The name for the new server. 
Example\: server1
    imageRef - The image reference to use for the server. This can be either an integer ID of an image or a string, which is the full URI of the image.
Examples\: 1242, https\://az-1.region-a.geo-1.compute.hpcloudsvc.com/v1.1/28400914814935/images/1242 
    flavorRef - The flavor to use for the new server. You can specify this as a simple ID or a complete URI.
Examples\: 101, https\://az-1.region-a.geo-1.compute.hpcloudsvc.com/v1.1/16634948504394/flavors/101
    keyName - The name of the security key used with the new server.
Example\: MyKey
    securityGroups - A JSON array of objects, each describing a security group. A server can be placed in multiple security groups, associating each of the security groups' rules with the server. 
Example\: [{"name"\:"group1"},{"name"\:"group2"}]
    adminPassword - The server administrator password. If this password does not meet the system security requirements, the server can enter an 'ERROR' state. In this case the  needs to be changed using the 'Change Server Admin Password'               operation. If this password does not meet the requirements, it might be ignored and a new random password is generated. 
    metadata - A JSON object which defines name/value metadata pairs for the new server.
Example\: { "My Server Name" \: "Apache1", "min_ram" \: "2" }
    personality - A JSON Array of objects each defining a file to inject into the new servers' file system. 
Example\: [{ "path" \: "/etc/banner.txt",  "contents" \: "ICAgICAgDQoiQSBjbG91ZCBkb2VzIG5vdCBrbm93IHdoeSBp dCBtb3ZlcyBpbiBqdXN0IHN1Y2ggYSBkaXJlY3Rpb24gYW5k IGF0IHN1Y2ggYSBzcGVlZC4uLkl0IGZlZWxzIGFuIGltcHVs c2lvbi4uLnRoaXMgaXMgdGhlIHBsYWNlIHRvIGdvIG5vdy4g QnV0IHRoZSBza3kga25vd3MgdGhlIHJlYXNvbnMgYW5kIHRo ZSBwYXR0ZXJucyBiZWhpbmQgYWxsIGNsb3VkcywgYW5kIHlv dSB3aWxsIGtub3csIHRvbywgd2hlbiB5b3UgbGlmdCB5b3Vy c2VsZiBoaWdoIGVub3VnaCB0byBzZWUgYmV5b25kIGhvcml6 b25zLiINCg0KLVJpY2hhcmQgQmFjaA\=\="   }]
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication)
Default value\: anonymous (no authentication used when executing the request)

794e9f35-28b1-48b1-9732-236c23d151a6.ef267f77-c665-490c-8baa-b2a8a81e8f35.description=
Adds a flow variable into the local context (available to itself and child flows only)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the flow variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];
flow.name: Create Server
